So let's first do a bit of factoring. Everywhere in mathematics, a safer way to figure things out is to see if what you're trying to do is a factoring problem in disguise, and thus performing a factorization. Here we see the polynomial $x^9 + 1.$ If this were, we would want to factor this into the form $(\text{something})(\text{something}(\text{something})(\text{something})).$ From here we see that $x^9 + 1 = (x + 1)(x^8 - x^7 + x^6 - x^5 + x^4 - x^3 + x^2 - x + 1).$积 Why? Is there a better way? What about the Remainder Theorem? No, because the Remainder Theorem only tells us what the remainder is, it doesn't tell us the actual value of $f(a)$, so we may as well see if we can factor it instead, which gets us a much better way to think about this problem. [source: Wolfram|Alpha]_()
